Posted @withrepost • @limorgarfinkle The first comedy club I ever visited when I first moved to NYC was @carolinesonbway back in ‘98 or ‘99. Caroline Hirsch is one of the most incredibly supportive and generous women I know. I am so grateful for all her support and for believing in me and in my Comedians photo series project, for hosting my first fundraiser as part of the NYCF lineup of events and my second at Caroline’s on Broadway. I am saddened that the Broadway location will no longer be there, I don’t know a NYC where that place does not exist, but knowing the incredible Ms. Hirsch, I have no doubt that something awesome is in the works. Cheers to the next chapter of Caroline’s! 🥂❤️

The picture is from the first fundraiser as part of the NYCF lineup. We had such an incredible lineup: @mindycohn, Margaret Colin, @jewdygold, @ryanhamiltone, @patbrownshow, @jaredfreid, @jimflorentine, @toddbarry,  @dannycohencomedy, @jodiewasserman and @jimgaffigan.

Buster Keaton, 1952
Courtesy Smithsonian’s National Museum of American History. Photographs by Richard Avedon.
One of the most popular and successful comic actors of the silent era, Buster Keaton
was an actor, director, producer, screenwriter and editor.  His elaborate stunt work, which he 
personally performed without camera edits, remains legendary to this day and an inspiration to this actor.
